<dl id="n14034a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n14" href="#n14034a">N14 (VI.B.7)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n14all.htm#n14034a"> 34(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> inner path <small>Ink</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">While, therefore, Rome was entirely imbued with the <i>historical</i> aspect of the Christ&mdash;the &ldquo;Crucified One&rdquo;&mdash;and beheld in the Church the Mediator between Him and Humanity, the German Mystics yearned for the <i>Presence</i> of Him Who had risen from the Dead&mdash;for the <i>living</i> Christ&mdash;and sought this union by means of the &ldquo;<mark>inner path</mark>&rdquo; in the depths of their own souls, seeking thus to breathe new life into the revelations of tradition. <small> Ernst Boldt, <a name="BFLS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BFLS"><cite title="source">From Luther to Steiner</cite></a>, (1921) 8</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Copied by George Joyce into <a name="sa0984cf" href="saall.htm#sa0984cf">SA (VI.A):0984(cf)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
